[3] Argentina (Salta)
Date: Thu 22 Apr 2010
Source: Infobae [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.infobae.com/salud/512627-101096-0-Un-nino-y-su-tia-jubilada-murieron-hantavirus-Salta>


A boy and his aunt died of a hantavirus infection. The victims aged
10 and 60, came to the hospital in "extremely critical" condition.
Another member of the family also is admitted to hospital due to the disease.

Both of the fatal [cases] resided in Oran, located north of Salta and
considered a hantavirus focus. Both died within days of each other,
stated the Diario La Prensa website. They lived in the Rio Blanco
settlement, west of the city, and were attended 15 days apart in the
San Vicente de Paul Hospital of Oran.

Julio Moreno, administrator of this health center, explained that the
2 patients, who died during this past month, came with "extremely
critical" clinical pictures. He confirmed also that a member of the
same family is admitted to hospital, although his [clinical] progress
is favorable.

"Years ago we had entire families who contracted the virus," the
physician sated, "which is why the [current] situation is not
considered a new one."

According to Moreno's statement, "it is this season when cases of
hantavirus [infection] are habitually registered." These days, it is
much easier to detect them, he continued, due to the fact that the
provincial laboratory of tropical diseases is located in Oran. This
specialist recalled that, before this center was established, "there
were deaths because erroneous treatment was given to hantavirus
[infection] cases, which could have been confused with dengue,"
because the symptomatology of both diseases "is similar, although the
treatment which must be given is diametrically opposed."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

The hantavirus present in Salta is likely to be Oran virus with its
sigmodontine rodent host being _Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_.

